  "signature": "ed25519:7a3c9f1e2b8d4a6c0f5e3b7d9a1c4f2e8b6d0a5c3f7e1b9d4a2c6f0e8b3d5a7",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA level 2 requires documented version control, regression test suite covering primary solver routines, and a traceable build record. Achieved when all three are demonstrated in the software quality plan.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 is used under an institutional SQA plan that includes version-controlled solver binaries, a 47-case regression suite run at each release, and an FDA-recognized software validation protocol. SQA Level 2 is sufficient for MRL 2 per Table 3 of ASME V&V 40-2018."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification at level 2 requires demonstration of order-of-accuracy convergence for at least one canonical internal-flow benchmark relevant to rotodynamic machinery.",
      "rationale": "Order-of-accuracy verification was performed using the method of manufactured solutions on a rotating-frame Navier-Stokes benchmark. Observed spatial order of accuracy of 1.94 ± 0.08 is consistent with the nominal second-order discretization scheme, satisfying Level 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Discretization error at level 2 requires a formal grid-convergence study with GCI < 5% on the primary QoI (scalar stress-based hemolysis index) across at least three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted (coarse 4.2 M cells, medium 11.7 M cells, fine 31.4 M cells) using the Grid Convergence Index methodology per ASME V&V 20. GCI on the volume-averaged power-law hemolysis index was 1.8% (medium-to-fine), well below the 5% threshold. The achieved level of 3 reflects the additional Richardson extrapolation uncertainty quantification performed beyond the minimum requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions at level 2 require that experimental boundary conditions (inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, and hematocrit) are documented with measurement uncertainty and shown to bound the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions replicated the five COU flow-speed combinations (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Phosphate-buffered saline with bovine red blood cells at 30% hematocrit was used. Inlet flow uncertainty was ±2.3% (ultrasonic flowmeter, ISO 9001 calibration). All conditions fall within the declared COU operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The output comparison factor addresses the degree to which simulation predictions of the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RHI) agree with experimental measurements across the five COU operating points. For MRL 2 with high decision consequence and medium model influence, a Gradation 2 requirement applies per Table 3 of ASME V&V 40-2018. The assessment team evaluated this factor against the validation dataset comprising 15 experimental replicates at each of the five operating points (n = 75 total). Predicted NIH values fell within one experimental standard deviation of the mean measured NIH at all five operating points. The RHI metric, defined as the ratio of model-predicted hemolysis for the test device to that of the predicate device, yielded values ranging from 0.71 to 0.89 across the operating envelope, all satisfying the RH < 1 criterion specified in the COU intended use. Bland-Altman analysis of predicted versus measured NIH showed a mean bias of −0.0023 g/100 L and 95% limits of agreement of ±0.018 g/100 L, which the team determined to be clinically acceptable given that the minimum clinically relevant difference in NIH for CPB applications is approximately 0.05 g/100 L. The turbulence model sensitivity study demonstrated that the SST k-omega model produced consistently lower bias than the realizable k-epsilon formulation (mean absolute error 8.4% vs. 14.1%), supporting selection of SST k-omega as the production turbulence closure. Particle-tracking path length sensitivity was evaluated by varying the maximum integration step from 0.1 to 0.5 mm; RHI varied by less than 1.2% across this range, confirming numerical robustness of the hemolysis integration scheme. The assessment team notes that the power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger coefficients) introduces model-form uncertainty that is partially captured in the output comparison but is more fully addressed under the Model Form factor. Taken together, the quantitative agreement metrics, the clinical relevance framing of the bias bounds, and the robustness studies collectively support a Gradation 2 achievement for this factor. The structured acceptance threshold documentation is consolidated in the project V&V plan (Morrison Lab Internal Report ML-VVP-2024-03, Section 4.7), which serves as the authoritative reference for this determination."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI relevance at level 2 requires that the selected simulation output quantities are directly traceable to the clinical or regulatory decision metric, with documented mapping between CFD outputs and the predicate comparison criterion.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH, g/100 L), which maps directly to the RHI = NIH_test / NIH_predicate metric used in the regulatory decision. The CFD-derived NIH integrates the power-law hemolysis damage model along particle trajectories throughout the blood-wetted volume, providing a direct computational analog to the bench-test measurement. This mapping is documented in the V&V plan."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity relevance at level 2 requires that validation experiments are conducted on a geometry and under conditions sufficiently similar to the COU that extrapolation uncertainty is bounded and documented.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry — the same geometry used in the COU simulations — at the five COU operating points. No geometric extrapolation is required. The validation fluid (bovine RBC in PBS at 30% Hct) is an accepted surrogate for human blood in hemolysis bench testing per FDA guidance. Validation activity relevance is therefore assessed as high, supporting Level 2 achievement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 2 with the achieved SQA and code verification evidence, a standalone numerical solver error assessment is not required; solver residual convergence to 1e-5 on all equations is documented as a proxy indicator.",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped to Level 1 at MRL 2 per Table 3. Residual convergence to 1×10⁻⁵ on continuity, momentum, and turbulence equations was confirmed at all operating points. No additional iterative error quantification is required at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Use error at level 1 requires only that the simulation was performed by personnel with documented CFD training relevant to rotodynamic blood pump analysis.",
      "rationale": "Simulations were executed by two PhD-level engineers with a combined 11 years of experience in cardiovascular CFD. Operator qualifications are documented in the personnel training records. Level 1 is sufficient at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form at level 2 requires documented justification for the choice of turbulence closure and hemolysis damage model, including sensitivity analysis demonstrating that alternative plausible model forms do not change the regulatory decision outcome.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its established performance in swirling confined flows. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was selected as the regulatory standard for comparative assessments. Sensitivity to turbulence model (SST k-omega vs. realizable k-epsilon) and hemolysis model coefficients (±20% perturbation) was evaluated; RHI remained below 1.0 in all sensitivity cases, confirming robustness of the regulatory decision to model form uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs at level 1 requires that all boundary condition values are traceable to a documented source (experimental measurement, manufacturer specification, or published literature).",
      "rationale": "All model inputs (inlet velocity profiles, rotational speed, fluid viscosity, density) are traceable to the experimental test protocol and published blood analog fluid properties. Level 1 is sufficient at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples at level 1 requires documentation of the blood analog fluid preparation protocol and confirmation that sample hematocrit was within ±2% of the target value.",
      "rationale": "Bovine RBC samples were prepared per ASTM F1841 protocols. Hematocrit was measured at 30.1 ± 0.8% (target 30%), within the ±2% tolerance. Level 1 is sufficient at MRL 2."
